userStories.notes:
Files:
- platform/browser-extension/src/side-panel/App.tsx (track error state, pass to SearchResults)
- platform/browser-extension/src/side-panel/components/SearchResults.tsx (render error)

Context:
The npm search is triggered in App.tsx lines 124-143. The `.catch()` at line 132 silently swallows errors:
```tsx
.catch(() => {
  if (npmSearchCounter.current === searchId) {
    setNpmResults([]);
  }
})
```

SearchResults.tsx renders the available section at lines 122-144. The 'No results' message at line 147:
```tsx
{showNoResults && <div className="py-8 text-center text-muted-foreground text-sm">No results</div>}
```

Changes:

1. In App.tsx, add a state variable:
```tsx
const [npmSearchError, setNpmSearchError] = useState(false);
```

2. In the search handler, set error state on catch and clear on success:
```tsx
.then(result => {
  if (npmSearchCounter.current === searchId) {
    setNpmResults(result.results);
    setNpmSearchError(false);
  }
})
.catch(() => {
  if (npmSearchCounter.current === searchId) {
    setNpmResults([]);
    setNpmSearchError(true);
  }
})
```

3. Clear error when search query is cleared (in the `if (!query.trim())` branch at line 118):
```tsx
if (!query.trim()) {
  setNpmResults([]);
  setNpmSearching(false);
  setNpmSearchError(false);
  return;
}
```

4. Pass `npmSearchError` to SearchResults:
```tsx
<SearchResults
  ...
  npmSearchError={npmSearchError}
/>
```

5. In SearchResults.tsx, accept the new prop and render error below the 'Available' section:
- Add `npmSearchError?: boolean` to SearchResultsProps
- After the npmSearching loader (line 123-125), add a branch for error state:
```tsx
npmSearchError ? (
  <div className="py-4 text-center text-muted-foreground text-sm">Search failed</div>
) : (
```

Constraints:
- Do NOT retry failed searches automatically — the user will naturally edit their query.
- Do NOT use an Alert component for this — match the existing 'No results' text style for consistency.
- Do NOT change the debounce timing or search counter logic.
- The error state is a simple boolean — no need to store the error message (npm errors are not user-actionable).
